\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
ROUTING SPECTRUM ALLOCATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RSA problem can be addressed as routing resolution and spectrum allocation
 iterative 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christodoulopoulos2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this approach the RSA problem, the greatest difficulty emerge, is the
 large number of conditions that poses the problem.
 This introduces greater computational complexity when calculating the optimal
 path for each request, in turn optimizing the allocation of spectrum, which
 ultimately translates into very large computing times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RSA problem in elastic optical networks is equivalent to the problem
 RWA networks.
 The difference between these two technologies is the ability of the elastic
 networks to an assignment of flexible spectrum to meet the data rate requested,
 where a set of contiguous slots of the spectrum is assigned to a connection.
 The following restrictions are taken into account when calculating the
 routing and spectrum allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• Spectrum Continuity.
 That means the same spectral allocation of resources on each link along
 a canal route.
 Restriction on WDM and EON.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• Spectrum contiguity (or adjacency).
 The subcarriers are adjacent to each other on a channel.
 Restriction on EON.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• Spectral Conflict.
 It is defined as spectrum allocation for non-overlapping of different channels
 on the same fiber.
 Restriction on WDM and EON.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basically RSA algorithms are concerned to allocate a fraction of optical
 spectrum for each connection request subject to the above restrictions.
 We see an example in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rsa_problem_figure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chatterjee2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as the constraints are met for a solution.
 A connection request from node 1 to node 4 that requires 2 adjoining slots
 to transmit data, we see the first figure in the 1-2-4 nodes, use the links
 1 and 4, there is 4 slots available in the link 1, but in the link 4 there
 is only one slot available, then this does not meet the condition of contiguity.
 The following figure shows the 1-2-3-4 node, use the links 1, 2 and 3,
 to establish a route.
 We see that in the three link's meet contiguity condition since the slots
 are they found together in three links.
 
\end_layout

