\begin_layout Section
RELATED WORK 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the RSA is considered a NP-Complete problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "IEEE:rsa-np-completo"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, it has been treated with several techniques, exact and heuristic, both
 for dynamic and static traffic.
 Among the exact techniques are the ILP, while among the heuristics are
 optimizations with Colony of Bees (BCO, Bee Colony Optimization) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rsa:bco"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Genetic Algorithms (GA, Genetic Algorithm) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rsa:enfoque4,rsa:kshortestpath,daoGA-RSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, among others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aco-based"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tabu-search"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different ILP models for small instances and different heuristics for more
 real scenarios have been used successfully to solve the RSA problem.
 As an example we can mention in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "christodoulopoulos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 an ILP model was proposed to minimize the use of the spectrum to serve
 a traffic matrix.
 The authors propose a method that divides the problem into two sub-problems,
 the first is the routing and the second is the spectrum assignment and
 solves them sequentially, using a route-based approach.
 They also propose a heuristic algorithm that serves the connections one-by-one
 sequentially.
 Then in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christodoulopoulos2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the authors extend their previous results including consideration of modulatio
n level.
 With this new consideration, a new problem was defined teh routing, modulation
 level and spectrum assignment (RMLSA), being outside the scope of this
 work.
 Other problems such as 
\shape italic
Fragmentation Aware and Dynamic Traffic
\shape default
 are also not considered 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "engopt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another ILP formulation and the proof that the RSA problem is a NP-complete
 problem can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "IEEE:rsa-np-completo"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhang2012rsa:restricciones2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the differences between an ILP for RWA and for RSA are exposed, as well
 as an algorithm complexity analysis.
 In the same work two RSA algorithms are exposed.
 These have a better performance than the ILP in larger networks.
 With these two heuristic algorithms, the computational time was reduced,
 which is considered an improvement compared with the ILP, with which it
 differentiates in computation hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moga-rsa-dao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, presents the multi-objective RSA problem and its associated algorithm
 model.
 Each request has many possible routes, and in each routing it has several
 spectrum assignment options.
 The problem is to minimize the spectrum width to support all requests and
 minimize the overall cost of the spectrum in the link.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective function for the work proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moga-rsa-dao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is as following: there are two objectives associated with each solution.
 The first objective 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

, is the width of the spectrum that indicates the maximum indexed slice
 used in the network.
 The second objective 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the total cost of the spectrum link.
 Given a set of requests, the route and channel are calculated for each
 one.
 After attending each demand sequentially and without any sort of ordering,
 the spectrum availabilities vector of each link is updated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work it is developed multi-objective approach to calculate a Pareto
 front.
 This approach is an extension of the work presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "engopt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which has an approach based on weighted sum.
 In our work, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moga-rsa-dao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 it has many possible routes, and in each routing it has several spectrum
 assignment options.
 The problem is to minimize the spectrum used and the overall cost of the
 link spectrum at the same time.
 The same objective function is taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moga-rsa-dao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the requests are handled as follows: applications are ordered from
 highest to lowest, defined by the highest possible cost of said request,
 the first 30% of said list is attended in the first place, while the remaining
 70% is treated in a random manner, unlike 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moga-rsa-dao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 it is a random ordering.
 More details are given in section 7.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
PARETO FRONT CONCEPTS 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is said that the solutions of a problem with multiple objectives are
 optimal because no other solution is superior to them when all the objectives
 and restrictions are taken into account at the same time.
 It can be said that no objective can be improved without degrading the
 other objectives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of optimal solutions is known as Pareto Optimal solutions, in which
 they have multiple objectives to meet and present conflicts when performing
 the simultaneous optimization of them.
 From this concept, it is established as a requirement to affirm that one
 situation is better than the other, which it does not diminish in anyone,
 but improve at one; that is to say that one situation will be better than
 another, only if in the new one it is possible to compensate the losses
 of all the injured parties.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pareto_figure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, you can see the optimal Pareto sets for different scenarios with two objective
s and for the same solution space.
 In any case, Pareto's optimum is always composed of solutions located at
 the edge of the feasible region of the solution space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pareto Dominance in a context of minimization says (Min-Min Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pareto_figure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

): that a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

 dominates another solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

if the following conditions are met: 1) the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

 is not worse than 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 in all the objectives.
 2) The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

 is strictly better than 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

in at least one objective.
 In Multi-objective Optimization is seeking to calculate the set of non-dominate
 solutions on the edge of the feasible region.
 
\end_layout

